Hello again. In the previous part, we were working on refactoring the blog auth, focused mostly on the client side. In this part we’ll touch on server-side auth—a bit more complicated, of course.
The goal is to handle transfer state for users. On the server, the app can prerender the whole HTML with data based on the logged-in user.
To achieve that, we need to install @supabase/ssr. It's a library from Supabase that handles transfers from server to client and vice versa. The first issue was that it didn't cover the Angular case—but that turned out to be no problem.
The second issue: do you remember that the server wasn’t waiting for Supabase API calls to finish requests?
The next issue is that Angular can’t handle the transfer state manually, so even if the server waits for the request to finish, the client will also do a request—and we lose all SSR benefits.
The last issues are related: we need to handle token refresh on the server, send back a token, and not mess with the cache. In the future I want to make the app cached so without proper cookies we could leak someone’s data to random users.

Platform-Aware Supabase Client
So the code looks like this right now:
projects/shared/src/core/supabase/supabase.client.tsexport function createSupabaseClient(): SupabaseClient | null {
const config = inject(SUPABASE_CONFIG);
const platform = inject(PLATFORM_ID);
const request = inject(REQUEST, { optional: true });
const responseInit = inject(RESPONSE_INIT, { optional: true });
if (isPlatformBrowser(platform)) {
return createBrowserClient(config.supabaseUrl, config.supabaseKey);
}
if (isPlatformServer(platform)) {
return createServerClient(config.supabaseUrl, config.supabaseKey, {
cookies: {
getAll: () =>
parseCookieHeader(request.headers.get('cookie') ?? '').map(c => ({
name: c.name,
value: c.value ?? '',
})),
setAll: (cookiesToSet, headers = {}) => {
if (!responseInit) return;
const responseHeaders = new Headers(responseInit.headers ?? undefined);
cookiesToSet.forEach(({ name, value, options }) => {
responseHeaders.append('Set-Cookie', serializeCookieHeader(name, value, options));
});
Object.entries(headers).forEach(([key, value]) => {
if (key.toLowerCase() === 'set-cookie') {
responseHeaders.append(key, value);
} else {
responseHeaders.set(key, value);
}
});
responseInit.headers = responseHeaders;
},
},
});
}
return null;
}
There’s a split between createBrowserClient() and createServerClient(). Hopefully Supabase handles almost all of it itself—we just need to configure cookies. This part was quite challenging, since there's no tutorial for Angular. I had to dig through Stack Overflow and compare tutorials written for other frameworks.
Another change: BrowserClient now uses a cookie instead of localStorage.
We need to handle incoming and outgoing cookies:

• getAll(): Reads cookies from the incoming request

• setAll(): Writes updated cookies to the response (e.g., after token refresh)
getAll() is pretty straightforward — we just parse all incoming cookies.
setAll() is more complicated. There are two loops that look similar:

• Loop 1 processes the cookiesToSet array (auth cookies)

• Loop 2 processes the headers object (cache control headers)
The first loop kicks in when, for example, the token is refreshed. The second one takes care of cache — we don’t want to cache this state, because we’re sending data that’s prerendered for a specific user. Anonymous users can get a cached response.
You might ask: if someone is logged in, will they wait longer for the app? Yes 😄. I know that’s not ideal, but this is an academic project, not a production-grade real-world app.

Handling Server-Side Auth
In the previous part, we set up client auth initialization. Now we need to provide the server-side counterpart:
private async handleServerSideAuth(): Promise<void> {
if (!this.client) return;
const { data } = await this.client.auth.getSession();
if (data.session?.user) {
const user = data.session.user as UserWithRole;
this.userService.setAppUser(user);
this.transferState.set(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY, user);
return;
}
this.userService.setAppUser(null);
this.transferState.set(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY, null);
}Looks fairly simple, and it is. We’re using it, which isn't recommended on the server side, but.getUser() is the better choice there.
Use getSession when you need the raw session (the access token, refresh token, and expiry) — for example, to forward the access token to another service. The session is loaded directly from local storage and isn't re-validated against the auth server, so the embedded user object shouldn't be trusted on its own when storage is shared with the client (cookies, request headers). To verify identity, validate the access token with getClaims, or call getUser for a fresh, server-confirmed user record.
It’s not recommended for authorization, but in this case we’re just fetching the username. I don’t think the GDPR police will be knocking on my door at 6:00 AM over a leak this small. On the other hand, the token still gets validated by RLS on the client side, so no sensitive data is actually exposed.

Transfer State
With the native HTTP client, everything happens automagically under the hood. In Angular this feature was later added to resources too, if I recall correctly — though an id property needs to be provided. A short snippet from the docs:
A key-value store that is transferred from the application on the server side to the application on the client side.
The TransferState is available as an injectable token. On the client, just inject this token using DI and use it — it will be lazily initialized. On the server it's already included if the renderApplication function is used; otherwise, import the ServerTransferStateModule to make TransferState available.
The values in the store are serialized/deserialized using JSON.stringify/JSON.parse. So only boolean, number, string, null, and non-class objects will be serialized and deserialized in a non-lossy manner.
I think we’ll need to double-check dates, to make sure everything comes through correctly.
Usage is pretty simple:
this.transferState.set(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY, user);Now we need to catch it on the client side:
if (this.transferState.hasKey(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY)) {
const user = this.transferState.get(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY, null);
this.userService.setAppUser(user);
this.transferState.remove(APP_USER_TRANSFER_KEY);
return;
}Pretty easy — we manually set the user data. We built a well-structured architecture earlier, which makes this part much simpler.

Profile Service with TransferState
For data that will be used across multiple screens—data with, say, an id or a different selector—we need to make sure the key is unique. So we'll use an ID suffix for that. As a final fallback, in case of some unexpected situation, an API call will be made.
export class ProfileService {
private readonly client = inject(SUPABASE_CLIENT);
private readonly transferState = inject(TransferState);
private readonly platformId = inject(PLATFORM_ID); getProfile(userId: string | undefined): Observable<Profile | null> {
const PROFILE_TRANSFER_KEY = makeStateKey<Profile | null>(`profile-${userId}`);
if (isPlatformServer(this.platformId)) {
return from(this.client.from('profiles').select('*').eq('id', userId).single()).pipe(
map(({ data, error }) => (error ? null : data)),
tap(profile => {
this.transferState.set(PROFILE_TRANSFER_KEY, profile);
})
);
}
if (this.transferState.hasKey(PROFILE_TRANSFER_KEY)) {
const profile = this.transferState.get(PROFILE_TRANSFER_KEY, null);
this.transferState.remove(PROFILE_TRANSFER_KEY);
return of(profile);
}
return from(this.client.from('profiles').select('*').eq('id', userId).single()).pipe(
map(({ data, error }) => (error ? null : data))
);
}
}
That’s pretty much it. It went fast — aside from the cookie handling — but I’ll show in a bit how I approached that.
A little polish
transfer-state-keys.util.ts — a small utility to help manage transfer state IDs. It's easy to accidentally reuse the same key in different places, so this gives us a single spot with all keys defined, and nobody ends up duplicating an ID.
export const TRANSFER_STATE_KEYS = {
APP_USER: makeStateKey<UserWithRole | null>('app-user'),
POSTS: makeStateKey<Post[]>('posts'),
TAGS: makeStateKey<Tag[] | null>('tags'),
PROFILES: makeStateKey<Profile[] | null>('profiles'),
} as const;export const createPostKey = (id: string): StateKey<Post | null> =>
makeStateKey<Post | null>(`post-${id}`);
export const createCommentsKey = (postId: string): StateKey<Comment[]> =>
makeStateKey<Comment[]>(`comments-${postId}`);
export const createProfileKey = (userId: string): StateKey<Profile | null> =>
makeStateKey<Profile | null>(`profile-${userId}`);
export const createPostTagsKey = (postId: string): StateKey<PostTag[] | null> =>
makeStateKey<PostTag[] | null>(`post-tags-${postId}`);
One more thing:pendingUntilEventChanged needs to run within an injection context, so we need to add an injector if we still want to use the input id.

Bonus: Tests
I’m trying to add tests to all my current blog posts. This time I was forced into TDD—I don’t love it, but here I knew exactly what output I wanted. What I didn’t know was how to achieve it or even how to test it, so Claude helped me write Playwright tests for it.
Everything below this point is AI-generated.
The challenge: how do we prove the server refreshed the token, not the browser?
Answer: disable JavaScript. Only SSR can update cookies in that scenario.
Test setup: creating a 10-second token
